Exploratory Data Analysis by Rahel Ghebrekidan

Introduction

The project intends to investigate the relation between quality of wine and factors that affect it quantitatively. The quality of red wine is affected by different factors starting from how the wine was growing till how it was served. Depending on the variables given on the dataset, I am going to explore the variables which has strong relationship with the quality.

The data set is about red variants of the Portuguese “Vihno Verde” wine. It is extracted from https://www.google.com/url?q=https://s3.amazonaws.com/udacity-hosted-downloads/ud651/wineQualityReds.csv&sa=D&ust=1469921568663000&usg=AFQjCNF3NKxn9msJJYuGQuy76gX_WdOa0A.

Objective of the project

  • Perform Univariate, bivariate and multivariate analysis on the variables in the Red wine data set
  • Transforming data to normalize variables distribution and/or remove outliers
  • Test correlation between the variables

Variables In the Data Set

## [1] 1599   13

There are 1599 rows(wines) and 13 variables in the data set.

The Variables and their unit

1 - X (case/raw number )
2 - Fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
3 - Volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
4 - Citric acid (g / dm^3)
5 - Residual sugar (g / dm^3)
6 - Chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3
7 - Free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
8 - Total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
9 - Density (g / cm^3)
10 - PH(scale from 0 to 14)
11 - Sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
12 - Alcohol (% by volume) 13 - Quality (score between 0 and 10)

Quality of Red Wine

Summary on Univariate analysis

The main futures of the dataset in regard to my topic of interest (quality of Red wine) are alcohol, sulphates and volatile acidity. These factors have greater impact on the quality of red wine compared to the other variables.

Density is partly dependent on alcohol concentration and pH is a scale showing how acidic or basic a wine is. Hence, I am interested in checking the relation between alcohol and density, and volatile acidity and pH.

In order to help me with some of my analysis, I have grouped the quality variable as ‘Not Good’, ‘Average’ and ‘Good’.

There are some variables which are not normally distributed and with outliers. I have made an effort to normalize and remove outliers as much as possible using log10 and limit functions. The variables which are not normally distributed or having outliers are free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides and alcohol.

The result shows the correlation between quality and alcohol, sulphates, and Volatile acidity is higher(positively and negatively) compared to other variables.

1. Alcohol

The Pearson correlation coefficent between quality and alcohol is 0.48. The relation between alcohol and red wine is positive which means as the concentration of alcohol increases quality of red wine.

The same as the result derived from Pearson correlation, the graph show positive relation between alcohol and quality.

2. Sulphates

The correlation between sulphates and quality is 0.25 which is a weak positive relation.

3. Volatile Acidity

The correlation between sulphates and quality is -0.39 which is negative relation.

It is clearly shown in the graph that as volite Acidity decreases quality increase except in the higher qualities where the change in Volatile acidity does not make any change.

Summary on Bivariate Analysis

After the Pearson correlation between quality and all the variable was checked, the coefficient of correlation is with alcohol, sulphate and volital acidity.Although the relation is not strong, it is higher betweeb the above mentioned variales and qualtiy. The relation is positive with alcohol and sulphate, and negative with volitale acidity.

Investigation was made to see if the attributes have relation among themselves other than with my topic of interest(quality), I have observed that alcohol and density has strong negative relation with Pearson Coefficient of correlation -0.50. Like wise, pH and fixed acidity have strong negative relation with -0.68 Pearson Coefficient of correlation.

The strongest relationship is between pH ad fixed acidity which is -0.68. pH and fixed Acidity has strong negative relation. While Alcohol has the strongest relation with quality of wine.

Multivariate Plots and Analysis

1. Alcohol and Density with Quality

Alcohol and density has positive relation. Their relation with quality is showing below.

The graph shows that as density decreases and alcohol increases, the quality was increasing with quality for certian degree of combination. When the combination is around 12 % of alchol and 0.99g/dm^3 of density the pattern change where the quality starts to decrease.

2. Free Sulfur dioxide and total Sulfur dioxide with Quality

As both free sulphur and total surfur increases the quality increases. However, the change in quality is the same for the average and good wines.

3. Alchol and Volatile Acidity with Quality

Refering the graph, we can say that with the increase of alcohol and the decrease of volatile, quality inceases as most of the ‘Good’ quality wine are on the top of the left corn of the graph.

Summary on Multivariate Analysis

The combined effect of the two variables with the quality was reflection of each variables effect on quality. However, the combinatin effect of free sulphur dioxide and total sulphur dioxide strenthened the quality of wine.

The effect of density and alcohol on quality is interest one. The quality increases with the increase in alcohol and the decrease in density but it starts to decrease at certain level as alcohol increases and density decreases.

Description Two

Plot Three: Fixed Acidity and PH with quality

Description Three

PH and fixed acidity has negative effect on quality when investigated individual. When exploring on their combined effect, the quality of wine is poor when PH level is high and fixed acidity is low but it doesn not show any relation for the average and good wines.

Reflection

The above investigation shows that the quality of wine is mainly affected by the concentration of alcohol especially at the lower level. The effect of alcohol was not also that much strong. Based on our data it is not easy to explain the effect of alcohol on wine other than show us the positive correlation.

In the dataset, the quality of wine was mostly dominated by average wines( quality value ‘5’ and ‘6’), there were very few bad( quality value ‘3’ or ‘4’). The number of wine which were level as ‘3’ and ‘4’ were 63, those which were level as ‘5’ or ‘6’ were 1319 and those with ‘7’ or ‘8’ are 217. So it was not easy noticeable to see the difference in most graphs. Even look at the quality with out groupping it does not show the effect clearly. It would have been good if the number of wines in each quality scale were the same and if we have very bad and excellent scaled wines.
